{{Quote|I wouldn't say this was just another job&mdash;there's no such thing as just another job&mdash;but I didn't realize how special it was going to be at the time.|George Roubicek on ''Star Wars''|<ref name="SWI">{{InsiderCite|96|The Men Who Built the Empire}}</ref>}}
'''George Roubicek''' (born [[May 25]], [[1930s#1935|1935]])<ref name="BFI" /> is an Austrian [[Wikipedia:Actor|actor]] who portrayed [[Nahdonnis Praji]] in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''A New Hope'']], although his voice was dubbed by a different actor.


==Biography==
{{Quote|I don't think anyone knew ''[what ''Star Wars'' was]'', except maybe George Lucas, and I'm not sure he knew all the time! We certainly didn't know.|George Roubicek about ''Star Wars''|<ref name="SWI" />}}
[[File:CommanderPraji.png|thumb|right|150px|George Roubicek as [[Nahdonnis Praji]] in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''A New Hope'']] (1977)]]
In [[1976]], Roubicek was cast in [[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''Star Wars'']], the first film in the [[Original trilogy|original ''Star Wars'' trilogy]], where he played the small role of a [[Commander/Legends|commander]] in the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Galactic Empire]], who was later given the name [[Nahdonnis Praji]]. He appeared early in the film, after the Imperial forces [[Battle of Tatooine (Galactic Civil War)|seize]] the [[Alliance to Restore the Republic/Legends|Rebel Alliance]] [[Starship/Legends|starship]] [[Tantive IV/Legends|''Tantive IV'']] and capture [[Princess/Legends|Princess]] [[Leia Organa Solo/Legends|Leia Organa]]. However, his lines were dubbed by an American actor, so the character's voice did not at all resemble that of Roubicek.<ref>Ross, Robert (2004). "George Roubicek: Director" (Notes). [[Wikipedia:Monkey (TV series)|''Monkey: The Thirteen Lost Episodes'']] ([[Wikipedia:DVD|DVD]]). [[Wikipedia:United Kingdom|United Kingdom]]: Fabulous Films.</ref> He appears in only seventeen seconds of the film,<ref>[[Star Wars: Episode IV A New Hope|''A New Hope'']] (1977), written and directed by [[George Lucas]].</ref> and his role consists of three sentences of dialogue spoken to [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]]. Identified in the script only as "Second [[Officer/Legends|Officer]],"<ref name="ANH">[[George Lucas|Lucas, George]] (1998). ''Script Facsimile: Star Wars: Episode 4: A New Hope'' (1 ed.). [[LucasBooks]]. p. 11. [[Wikipedia:International Standard Book Number|ISBN]] [[Wikipedia:Special:BookSources/0819602655|0345420802]].</ref> the character was not given the name Praji until nearly two decades later with the [[1995]] release of the [[Premiere Limited]] set of [[Decipher, Inc.]]'s [[Star Wars Customizable Card Game]].<ref>[[Star Wars Customizable Card Game]] – [[Premiere Limited]] (Card: Commander Praji)</ref> The character's first name, Nahdonnis, was not identified until September [[2007]], when it was featured in the ''[[Star Wars Insider]]'' article "[[The Empire's Finest: Who's Who in the Imperial Military]]."<ref name="Insider 96">{{InsiderCite|96|The Empire's Finest: Who's Who in the Imperial Military}}</ref>

Roubicek's scene was filmed over a three-day period in [[July]] 1976, around the final days of [[Wikipedia:Principal photography|principal photography]]. Roubicek did not anticipate at the time that ''[[Star Wars]]'' would become such a cultural phenomenon&mdash;his first impression of the franchise was wondering what it was "all about." During a 2007 interview, Roubicek indicated that he had had no idea of the cultural impact the ''Star Wars'' film would eventually have, nor had he believed anyone else involved quite understood it either.<ref name="SWI" /> In 2007, three decades after the first theatrical release of ''Star Wars'' (later renamed ''A New Hope'') in [[1977]], Roubicek's image was used for a Commander Praji 12-inch [[action figure]] issued by [[Sideshow Collectibles]]. In a review of the figure, the designer toy website ''Plastic and Plush'' noted the sculpt mostly resembled the actor, but that it was difficult to capture his likeness because he did not have a very distinctive look.<ref name="P&P">{{WebCite|url=http://plasticandplush.com/2008/06/review-commande.html|text=REVIEW: Commander Praji 1/6 Scale|date=2008-06-01|work=[http://plasticandplush.com Plastic and Plush]|archivedate=20201202010046}}</ref> Roubicek has participated in and signed autographs at several ''Star Wars'' conventions, including [[Celebration IV]] in [[Wikipedia:Los Angeles|Los Angeles]], [[Wikipedia:California|California]] in 2007,<ref name="Jedi Insider">{{WebCite|url=http://jediinsider.com/index.php?catid=251&itemid=10066|text=Stars Shineat Celebration IV|date=2007-03-03|work=[https://jediinsider.com Jedi Insider]|archivedate=20170625091106}}</ref> and [[Celebration V]] in [[Wikipedia:Orlando, Florida|Orlando]], [[Wikipedia:Florida|Florida]] in [[2010]].<ref name="SW Celeb V">{{SWArchive|url=fans/events/celebration_v_autograph_guests/index.html|text=More Autograph Stars Coming to Celebration V}}</ref><ref name="Guests">{{Celebration|url=en/Guests|text=Guests|celebration=[[Celebration V]]|nolive=1}}</ref>

